result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica F Busack was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-Heroin (<=3g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(d)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant eligible for Challenge Incarceration and Substance Abuse programs after having served 2 years in prison.

superMiscConds.notes: If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.
Defendant shall not possess any weapons.

Defendant shall not possess or consume alcohol, drug paraphernalia or controlled substances without a valid prescription.
Defendant shall not enter any establishment where the primary purpose is the sale or service of alcohol. 
Defendant shall not have direct or indirect contact with David J. without prior approval of her supervising agent. 
Defendant shall not associate with known drug users or dealers.

Defendant shall pay all Dept of Corrections supervision fees. 
Defendant shall participate in an AODA assessment, a mental health evaluation and all counseling or treatment programs as directed by her supervising agent.
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample. 
Defendant shall take medications as prescribed. 
Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety. 
Defendant shall submit to random drug screens.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or school or a combination thereof. 
Defendant shall advise all her health care providers of her addiction history. 
Defendant shall advise her supervising agent of medical providers she is seeing and advise agent within 48 hours of being prescribed medications or changes to prescribed medications.
